  "Metadata" -> {
   "built" -> "{2026, 4, 12, 17, 59, 54.718003}", 
    "history" -> {"14.1", "", "", ""}, "context" -> "QuantumMob`Q3`", 
    "keywords" -> {}, "specialkeywords" -> {}, 
    "tutorialcollectionlinks" -> {}, "index" -> True, "label" -> 
    "Quantum Mob/ Q3 Tech Note", "language" -> "en", "paclet" -> 
    "QuantumMob/Q3", "status" -> "None", "summary" -> 
    "Majorana fermions, also known as Majorana particles, are a class of \
fermions that are their own antiparticles. This unique property distinguishes \
them from Dirac fermions, which have distinct particles and antiparticles. \
The concept was first proposed by Italian physicist Ettore Majorana in 1937. \
Mathematically, any fermionic system may be describe in terms of either Dirac \
or Majorana fermions. Roughly, one may regard a Majorana fermion as a half of \
Dirac fermion; in other words, a Dirac fermion may be regarded to consist of \
two Majorana fermions. Let a_ 1,\\[Ellipsis], a_n be Dirac fermion modes, and \
suppose that c_ 1,c_ 2,\\[Ellipsis],c_ 2n-1,c_ 2n be the corresponding \
Majorana modes. The transformation rules between Dirac fermion operators a_k \
and a_k^\\[Dagger] and the Majorana fermion operators c_ 2k-1 and c_ 2k are \
given by", "synonyms" -> {}, "tabletags" -> {}, "title" -> 
    "Majorana Fermions", "titlemodifier" -> "", "metadescription" -> "", 
    "windowtitle" -> "Majorana Fermions", "type" -> "Tech Note", "uri" -> 
    "QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/MajoranaFermions"}},
